{"bloom_level": "apply", "chosen": "If your goal is to describe what a property means, RDFS is the right tool: declare domain and range, let the reasoner derive class membership, and trust that consumers who reuse your terms will get useful entailments. If your goal is to validate that incoming data uses your property correctly — that nobody, ever, asserts ex:author with a non-Document subject — you need SHACL, which is the focus of Weeks 7 through 9. The right division of labor is: RDFS to publish meaning, SHACL to enforce constraints, OWL to express richer logic.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00054", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_61a3117e990e87f0", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00054_012", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-07", "to-02"], "lo_refs": ["co-07", "to-02"], "misconception_id": "mc_9590909414be48b4", "prompt": "Explain rdfs clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "\"If I declare ex:author rdfs:domain ex:Document, then a triple ex:alice ex:author ex:bob — where ex:alice is a Person, not a Document — will be flagged as a constraint violation; an RDFS validator will reject the graph.\" This treats RDFS as a type-checked schema language. It is not.", "seed": 12, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00054", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00054]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.3, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s3"}]}
{"chosen": "If your goal is to describe what a property means, RDFS is the right tool: declare domain and range, let the reasoner derive class membership, and trust that consumers who reuse your terms will get useful entailments. If your goal is to validate that incoming data uses your property correctly — that nobody, ever, asserts ex:author with a non-Document subject — you need SHACL, which is the focus of Weeks 7 through 9. The right division of labor is: RDFS to publish meaning, SHACL to enforce constraints, OWL to express richer logic.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00054", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_fa17a8613f49848b", "lo_refs": ["co-07", "to-02"], "misconception_id": "mc_9590909414be48b4", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about rdfs. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with rdfs, \"If I declare ex:author rdfs:domain ex:Document, then a triple ex:alice ex:author ex:bob &mdash; where ex:alice is a Person, not a Document &mdash; will be flagged as a constraint violation; an RDFS validator will reject the graph.\" This treats RDFS as a type-checked schema language. It is not. That's a fair summary and you can rely on it.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 70, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00054", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00054]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.3, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s3"}]}
