{"chosen": "Interpret datatyped literals and language-tagged strings, including lexical-to-value mapping for xsd types, when reading or producing RDF data. CO-05: Model a small real-world scenario as an RDF graph, choosing IRIs, vocabularies, and blank nodes appropriate to the domain. A correct response describes rdf accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00032", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_de2ff630f7201c3c", "lo_refs": ["co-04", "co-05", "to-01"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with rdf clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Interpret datatyped literals and language-tagged strings, including lexical-to-value mapping for xsd types, when reading or producing RDF data. CO-05: Model a small real-world scenario as an RDF graph, choosing IRIs, vocabularies, and blank nodes appropriate to the domain. A rough response alludes to rdf loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about rdf in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 48, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00032", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00032]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s50"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s52"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s61"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s65"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s60"}]}
{"bloom_level": "analyze", "chosen": "Train yourself to mentally expand every compact name on every read. When you see foaf:Person, hear \"http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/Person\"; when you see schema:NewsArticle, hear \"http://schema.org/NewsArticle.\" A useful tool is to run an unfamiliar Turtle or JSON-LD file through a converter like rdflib or rapper in N-Triples mode — the output has no prefixes at all, so the IRIs you actually committed to are exposed. The N-Triples view is the truth; the Turtle view is a presentation layer.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00036", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_7b4a27da5767f5c1", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00036_011", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-04", "to-01"], "lo_refs": ["co-04", "to-01"], "misconception_id": "mc_36966254db957beb", "prompt": "Explain rdf clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "\"The compact name foaf:Person is what identifies the FOAF Person class. Two RDF files that both use foaf:Person are talking about the same thing because they both use the same name; two files that use different prefix names — foaf:Person in one file and f:Person in another — are talking about different classes.\" This treats the alias as if it were the identity.", "seed": 11, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00036", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00036]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s21"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s52"}, {"confidence": 0.9, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s17"}, {"confidence": 0.9, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s29"}, {"confidence": 0.9, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s62"}]}
{"chosen": "Train yourself to mentally expand every compact name on every read. When you see foaf:Person, hear \"http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/Person\"; when you see schema:NewsArticle, hear \"http://schema.org/NewsArticle.\" A useful tool is to run an unfamiliar Turtle or JSON-LD file through a converter like rdflib or rapper in N-Triples mode — the output has no prefixes at all, so the IRIs you actually committed to are exposed. The N-Triples view is the truth; the Turtle view is a presentation layer.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00036", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_265f0d04d05f73f4", "lo_refs": ["co-04", "to-01"], "misconception_id": "mc_36966254db957beb", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about rdf. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with rdf, \"The compact name foaf:Person is what identifies the FOAF Person class. Two RDF files that both use foaf:Person are talking about the same thing because they both use the same name; two files that use different prefix names &mdash; foaf:Person in one file and f:Person in another &mdash; are talking about different classes.\" This treats the alias as if it were the identity. That's a fair summary and you can rely on it.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 52, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00036", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00036]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s21"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s52"}, {"confidence": 0.9, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s17"}, {"confidence": 0.9, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s29"}, {"confidence": 0.9, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s62"}]}
{"chosen": "Content 5 spelled out the open-world assumption (OWA) abstractly. This example shows OWA mattering on a small concrete graph. A correct response describes rdf accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00080", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_02ebb0d6aff93b02", "lo_refs": ["co-08", "co-23", "to-02", "to-06"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with rdf clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Content 5 spelled out the open-world assumption (OWA) abstractly. This example shows OWA mattering on a small concrete graph. A rough response alludes to rdf loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree rdf is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 96, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00080", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00080]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.7, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s4"}]}
{"chosen": "Week 10 · CO-24 · Worked example using the Primer's family ontology Before writing the chain axiom, we need a small family ontology to anchor the derivation. The OWL 2 Primer uses a family ontology throughout its examples; we follow the same shape here. A correct response describes rdf accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00233", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_146438575bac37d6", "lo_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with rdf clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Week 10 · CO-24 · Worked example using the Primer's family ontology Before writing the chain axiom, we need a small family ontology to anchor the derivation. The OWL 2 Primer uses a family ontology throughout its examples; we follow the same shape here. A rough response alludes to rdf loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about rdf in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 249, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00233", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00233]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
{"bloom_level": "remember", "chosen": "IRIs are identifiers; some happen to be dereferenceable HTTP URLs (Linked Data style), but the data model does not require it. The primer is explicit: 'Other forms of IRI provide an identifier for a resource without implying its location or how to access it.'", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00003", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_f47a2b5fd1944a47", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00003_004", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-02", "to-01"], "lo_refs": ["co-02", "to-01"], "misconception_id": "mc_9689eb5da72c3808", "prompt": "Explain iri clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "Every IRI is a URL you can resolve in a browser. This correction keeps the learner grounded in iri rather than a misleading shortcut.", "seed": 4, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00003", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00003]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.3, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s1"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s7"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "role": "corroborating", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_concepts_accessible#s2"}]}
