{"chosen": "The primer's Example 12 renders the Bob graph in JSON-LD. Read it slowly: { \"@context\": \"http://example.org/example-context.json\", \"@id\": \"http://example.org/bob#me\", \"@type\": \"Person\", \"name\": \"Bob\", \"birthDate\": \"1990-07-04\", \"knows\": \"http://example.org/alice#me\", \"topic_interest\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mona_Lisa\" } Walk through what this expands to. A correct response describes worth knowing accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00027", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_2a82ea3a1aadd97f", "lo_refs": ["co-04", "co-05", "to-01"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with worth knowing clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "The primer's Example 12 renders the Bob graph in JSON-LD. Read it slowly: { \"@context\": \"http://example.org/example-context.json\", \"@id\": \"http://example.org/bob#me\", \"@type\": \"Person\", \"name\": \"Bob\", \"birthDate\": \"1990-07-04\", \"knows\": \"http://example.org/alice#me\", \"topic_interest\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Mona_Lisa\" } Walk through what this expands to. A rough response alludes to worth knowing loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about worth knowing in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 43, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00027", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00027]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s28"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s29"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s61"}, {"confidence": 0.95, "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:rdf11_primer_accessible#s62"}]}
{"bloom_level": "apply", "chosen": "If your goal is to describe what a property means, RDFS is the right tool: declare domain and range, let the reasoner derive class membership, and trust that consumers who reuse your terms will get useful entailments. If your goal is to validate that incoming data uses your property correctly — that nobody, ever, asserts ex:author with a non-Document subject — you need SHACL, which is the focus of Weeks 7 through 9. The right division of labor is: RDFS to publish meaning, SHACL to enforce constraints, OWL to express richer logic.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00055", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_7a8166c85fea0da4", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00055_013", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-07", "to-02"], "lo_refs": ["co-07", "to-02"], "misconception_id": "mc_9590909414be48b4", "prompt": "Explain rdfs clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "\"If I declare ex:author rdfs:domain ex:Document, then a triple ex:alice ex:author ex:bob — where ex:alice is a Person, not a Document — will be flagged as a constraint violation; an RDFS validator will reject the graph.\" This treats RDFS as a type-checked schema language. It is not.", "seed": 13, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00055", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00055]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.3, "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s3"}]}
