{"chosen": "Common Pitfall: treating OPTIONAL like a filter When learners first reach for OPTIONAL , they typically reach for it because they want to exclude rows where a particular triple is missing — the way WHERE x IS NULL works in SQL. They write something like OPTIONAL { ?person foaf:mbox ?email . A correct response describes inside accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00110", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_31fc0927cef0abd6", "lo_refs": ["co-12", "to-03"], "misconception_id": "mc_c7933af7d937b634", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about inside. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with inside, \"OPTIONAL is just like a regular triple pattern but graceful — if the triple matches, great; if it doesn't, the row is still included; and a FILTER inside the OPTIONAL can require the optional bindings to satisfy some condition, dropping rows that fail.\" This sounds intuitive but conflates two different operators: OPTIONAL (left-join, never drops rows from the left side) and FILTER (predicate over a single solution, drops rows that fail). They cannot be composed by nesting one inside the other to produce conditional inclusion.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 126, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00110", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00110]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#53c5b5712ac5afa8"}, {"confidence": 0.7, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#6701991215d9bdb5"}]}
{"chosen": "You inherit the following query from a former teammate. The filter is at the same level as the OPTIONAL , so it evaluates per joined solution. Many learners try to fix this query by moving the filter inside the OPTIONAL : OPTIONAL { ?person ex:officeNumber ?office . A correct response describes plan trace the ebv accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00111", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_f7e9a7a5b35762d6", "lo_refs": ["co-12", "to-03"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with plan trace the ebv clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "You inherit the following query from a former teammate. The filter is at the same level as the OPTIONAL , so it evaluates per joined solution. Many learners try to fix this query by moving the filter inside the OPTIONAL : OPTIONAL { ?person ex:officeNumber ?office . A rough response alludes to plan trace the ebv loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about plan trace the ebv in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 127, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00111", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00111]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#b59dd96efbe6319e"}, {"confidence": 0.7, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#25ba4fe7efa83f42"}]}
{"chosen": "In Weeks 1 through 4 of this course you learned how to model the world as RDF triples and how to declare reusable vocabularies with RDF Schema. This week introduces SPARQL 1.1 , the W3C-standard query language for RDF defined in the SPARQL 1.1 Query Language Recommendation. A correct response describes sparql 11 accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00109", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_223ff548b756dbef", "lo_refs": ["co-11", "co-12", "to-03", "co-09", "to-02"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with sparql 11 clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "In Weeks 1 through 4 of this course you learned how to model the world as RDF triples and how to declare reusable vocabularies with RDF Schema. This week introduces SPARQL 1.1 , the W3C-standard query language for RDF defined in the SPARQL 1.1 Query Language Recommendation. A rough response alludes to sparql 11 loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about sparql 11 in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 125, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00109", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00109]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#f1221b72c605c26a"}, {"confidence": 0.75, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#2da0210f90dacd30"}]}
{"chosen": "If you arrive at SPARQL from a SQL background, the first thing that strikes you is that there is no JOIN keyword and no FROM in the usual sense. There is just a curly-brace block holding triple patterns. A correct response describes graph pattern matching accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00098", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_c4b7b4a4288d181b", "lo_refs": ["co-11", "to-03"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with graph pattern matching clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "If you arrive at SPARQL from a SQL background, the first thing that strikes you is that there is no JOIN keyword and no FROM in the usual sense. There is just a curly-brace block holding triple patterns. A rough response alludes to graph pattern matching loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about graph pattern matching in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 114, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00098", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00098]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#2da0210f90dacd30"}, {"confidence": 0.75, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:sparql11_query_accessible#46e9ccd13cf06b9a"}]}
