{"chosen": "Week 11 · CO-25 · Reading the validated, enriched graph through SPARQL By the time SPARQL runs in the pipeline, the heavy lifting is done. The data graph has been ingested into RDF, validated by SHACL, and enriched by an OWL 2 reasoner. A correct response describes select accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00254", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_eeff357879d8c3b7", "lo_refs": ["co-25", "to-06"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with select clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Week 11 · CO-25 · Reading the validated, enriched graph through SPARQL By the time SPARQL runs in the pipeline, the heavy lifting is done. The data graph has been ingested into RDF, validated by SHACL, and enriched by an OWL 2 reasoner. A rough response alludes to select loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about select in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 270, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00254", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00254]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s11"}]}
{"chosen": "A subquery in SPARQL is a complete SELECT query embedded inside the WHERE clause of another query. It runs first; its projected variables become bindings that the outer query can join, filter, and aggregate further. A correct response describes mental model accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00126", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_e914c986819160f3", "lo_refs": ["to-03"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with mental model clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "A subquery in SPARQL is a complete SELECT query embedded inside the WHERE clause of another query. It runs first; its projected variables become bindings that the outer query can join, filter, and aggregate further. A rough response alludes to mental model loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about mental model in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 142, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00126", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00126]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s6"}]}
{"chosen": "Subqueries add a query level, and each query level is its own evaluation scope with its own planner pass. That has two downsides. A correct response describes mental model accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00127", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_7ceaf4ce2b62aa1b", "lo_refs": ["to-03"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with mental model clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Subqueries add a query level, and each query level is its own evaluation scope with its own planner pass. That has two downsides. A rough response alludes to mental model loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of mental model aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 143, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00127", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00127]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s6"}]}
{"chosen": "The single most common bug in hand-written SPARQL aggregate queries is using FILTER where HAVING is required (or, less often, the reverse). The two clauses look syntactically similar — both take a boolean expression and drop the rows for which it is false — but they fire at radically different points in the evaluation pipeline, and the difference shows up the instant aggregate functions enter... A correct response describes mental shorthand accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00134", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_860ad59d6dd5adce", "lo_refs": ["co-13", "to-03"], "misconception_id": "mc_94b9fbb5f72a887d", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about mental shorthand. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with mental shorthand, \"FILTER and HAVING are basically the same — both drop unwanted rows from a query, and you can use either one to filter results based on aggregate values like COUNT(?x) or SUM(?price).\" Many learners arrive at this idea because the two clauses both express threshold logic and because in SQL the analogous distinction is sometimes blurred at the surface syntax. They reason: \"It is just a predicate that drops rows; what does it matter where I write it?\" — and they reach for FILTER because it is the clause they used in Week 5.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 150, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00134", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00134]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s6"}]}
