{"chosen": "SPARQL 1.1 defines four query forms because RDF answers four shapes of question. The specification is direct: \"SPARQL has four query forms. A correct response describes quick recall accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00122", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_8b276f4d082459d7", "lo_refs": ["co-14", "to-03"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with quick recall clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "SPARQL 1.1 defines four query forms because RDF answers four shapes of question. The specification is direct: \"SPARQL has four query forms. A rough response alludes to quick recall loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree quick recall is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 138, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00122", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00122]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s6"}]}
{"chosen": "DESCRIBE returns \"a single result RDF graph containing RDF data about resources\" — but the precise content of that graph is intentionally implementation-defined. The form has two argument shapes: DESCRIBE # describe a known IRI directly DESCRIBE ?p WHERE { ?p foaf:name \"Alice\" } # describe whatever IRIs the WHERE pattern binds Because output is... A correct response describes quick recall accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00123", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_63f9132865f22e8d", "lo_refs": ["co-14", "co-09", "to-03", "to-02"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with quick recall clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "DESCRIBE returns \"a single result RDF graph containing RDF data about resources\" — but the precise content of that graph is intentionally implementation-defined. The form has two argument shapes: DESCRIBE # describe a known IRI directly DESCRIBE ?p WHERE { ?p foaf:name \"Alice\" } # describe whatever IRIs the WHERE pattern binds Because output is... A rough response alludes to quick recall loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about quick recall in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 139, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00123", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00123]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s6"}]}
{"chosen": "A handful of patterns recur often enough that they are worth memorizing: Direct type plus all ancestor types. ?x rdf:type/rdfs:subClassOf* ?type binds ?type to every direct type of ?x and to every transitive supertype of those types. A correct response describes direct type plus all accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00125", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_f5dbccaed3bc7d49", "lo_refs": ["co-15", "to-03"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with direct type plus all clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "A handful of patterns recur often enough that they are worth memorizing: Direct type plus all ancestor types. ?x rdf:type/rdfs:subClassOf* ?type binds ?type to every direct type of ?x and to every transitive supertype of those types. A rough response alludes to direct type plus all loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree direct type plus all is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 141, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00125", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00125]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s6"}]}
{"chosen": "SPARQL 1.1 defines a fixed set of aggregate functions, each of which the specification calls a \"set function\" because it maps a multiset of values to a single value: COUNT(expr) — the number of bindings in the group for which expr evaluates without error. COUNT(*) counts solutions regardless of variable binding. A correct response describes reading strategy accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00121", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_5cb93ef1e0b7a2c2", "lo_refs": ["co-13", "to-03"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with reading strategy clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "SPARQL 1.1 defines a fixed set of aggregate functions, each of which the specification calls a \"set function\" because it maps a multiset of values to a single value: COUNT(expr) — the number of bindings in the group for which expr evaluates without error. COUNT(*) counts solutions regardless of variable binding. A rough response alludes to reading strategy loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of reading strategy aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 137, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00121", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00121]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s6"}]}
