{"chosen": "Financial-services firms run continuous data-quality validation on customer master records because regulators require it. Traditional approaches use stored procedures or a procedural ETL stage that catches \"missing tax-residency\" or \"malformed SSN\" by raising application-level exceptions. A correct response describes auditor sanity check accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00165", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_9ea9bfc3074299ca", "lo_refs": ["co-17", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with auditor sanity check clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Financial-services firms run continuous data-quality validation on customer master records because regulators require it. Traditional approaches use stored procedures or a procedural ETL stage that catches \"missing tax-residency\" or \"malformed SSN\" by raising application-level exceptions. A rough response alludes to auditor sanity check loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of auditor sanity check aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 181, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00165", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00165]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#56204d5fd74aa93f"}, {"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#dc21cc2d99e62b9c"}]}
{"chosen": "SHACL Core defines three severity levels ( sh:Info , sh:Warning , sh:Violation ) that flow from the shape's sh:severity declaration onto every sh:resultSeverity in the validation report. ex:Gizmo a ex:Product ; ex:name \"Gizmo\" ; ex:partNumber \"GIZ-001\" . A correct response describes authoring discipline accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00155", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_720d3bf5ce0f38ea", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with authoring discipline clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "SHACL Core defines three severity levels ( sh:Info , sh:Warning , sh:Violation ) that flow from the shape's sh:severity declaration onto every sh:resultSeverity in the validation report. ex:Gizmo a ex:Product ; ex:name \"Gizmo\" ; ex:partNumber \"GIZ-001\" . A rough response alludes to authoring discipline loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of authoring discipline aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 171, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00155", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00155]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#7855928147c8eafe"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#87f9dfcde0673761"}]}
{"chosen": "The output of every SHACL run is itself an RDF graph. The specification names this graph the validation report and gives it a single root node typed sh:ValidationReport . A correct response describes authoring tip accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00151", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_587d8f55c11b5f71", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with authoring tip clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "The output of every SHACL run is itself an RDF graph. The specification names this graph the validation report and gives it a single root node typed sh:ValidationReport . A rough response alludes to authoring tip loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree authoring tip is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 167, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00151", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00151]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#7855928147c8eafe"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#87f9dfcde0673761"}]}
{"chosen": "Every shape declares (or inherits) an sh:severity level, which is copied onto every result it produces as sh:resultSeverity . SHACL Core defines exactly three severity levels: sh:Info (informational; the result is recorded but the shape is intentionally permissive), sh:Warning (an issue worth attention but not blocking), and sh:Violation (the default; a real failure). A correct response describes authoring tip accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00152", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_0873c669ff3d826c", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with authoring tip clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Every shape declares (or inherits) an sh:severity level, which is copied onto every result it produces as sh:resultSeverity . SHACL Core defines exactly three severity levels: sh:Info (informational; the result is recorded but the shape is intentionally permissive), sh:Warning (an issue worth attention but not blocking), and sh:Violation (the default; a real failure). A rough response alludes to authoring tip loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about authoring tip in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 168, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00152", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00152]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#7855928147c8eafe"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#87f9dfcde0673761"}]}
{"chosen": "Most production SHACL deployments are not validating internal data — they are validating data flowing in from partners and external publishers. The validation problem there is harder than the internal case in two ways. A correct response describes generalizes to every partner accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00166", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_a2722d0f8215f8ea", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-17", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with generalizes to every partner clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Most production SHACL deployments are not validating internal data — they are validating data flowing in from partners and external publishers. The validation problem there is harder than the internal case in two ways. A rough response alludes to generalizes to every partner loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree generalizes to every partner is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 182, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00166", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00166]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#61eb3930a076d977"}, {"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#56204d5fd74aa93f"}]}
{"bloom_level": "understand", "chosen": "If you genuinely want a rule that does not affect conformance, the rule is not a SHACL shape.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00158", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_7d941b8464862802", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00158_026", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-16", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_d8531dd5129859a6", "prompt": "Explain operational consequence clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "\"If I want a SHACL rule to fire and produce a result but not cause the run to fail, I declare sh:severity sh:Warning on the shape. The processor will then emit the result with sh:resultSeverity sh:Warning and the report's sh:conforms will remain true, so the CI pipeline that checks sh:conforms will pass.\" This treats sh:Warning as a non-blocking severity in the mathematical sense, which is the wrong mental model.", "seed": 26, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00158", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00158]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#7855928147c8eafe"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#87f9dfcde0673761"}]}
{"chosen": "If you genuinely want a rule that does not affect conformance, the rule is not a SHACL shape.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00158", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_39f78b35da434fcb", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_d8531dd5129859a6", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about operational consequence. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with operational consequence, \"If I want a SHACL rule to fire and produce a result but not cause the run to fail, I declare sh:severity sh:Warning on the shape. The processor will then emit the result with sh:resultSeverity sh:Warning and the report's sh:conforms will remain true, so the CI pipeline that checks sh:conforms will pass.\" This treats sh:Warning as a non-blocking severity in the mathematical sense, which is the wrong mental model. That's a fair summary and you can rely on it.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 174, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00158", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00158]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#7855928147c8eafe"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#87f9dfcde0673761"}]}
