{"chosen": "The four target forms ( sh:targetClass , sh:targetNode , sh:targetSubjectsOf , sh:targetObjectsOf ) often produce strikingly different focus-node sets on the same data graph. This example exercises all four against one fixed data graph so the contrast is visible. A correct response describes type light data graphs accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00154", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_0b613757c2c3eea1", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-18", "co-19", "co-22", "to-04", "to-05"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with type light data graphs clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "The four target forms ( sh:targetClass , sh:targetNode , sh:targetSubjectsOf , sh:targetObjectsOf ) often produce strikingly different focus-node sets on the same data graph. This example exercises all four against one fixed data graph so the contrast is visible. A rough response alludes to type light data graphs loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about type light data graphs in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 170, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00154", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00154]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#61eb3930a076d977"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#56204d5fd74aa93f"}]}
{"chosen": "Requirement: \"Every Customer in our master graph must have exactly one tax-residency country, expressed as an ISO-3166 alpha-2 code.\" Apply the procedure: Population: \"every Customer.\" Reliable rdf:type ex:Customer coverage assumed. Target: sh:targetClass ex:Customer . A correct response describes identify the population accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00162", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_7174e386f9aee209", "lo_refs": ["co-17", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with identify the population clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Requirement: \"Every Customer in our master graph must have exactly one tax-residency country, expressed as an ISO-3166 alpha-2 code.\" Apply the procedure: Population: \"every Customer.\" Reliable rdf:type ex:Customer coverage assumed. Target: sh:targetClass ex:Customer . A rough response alludes to identify the population loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree identify the population is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 178, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00162", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00162]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#56204d5fd74aa93f"}, {"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#dc21cc2d99e62b9c"}]}
{"chosen": "Before we read the SHACL specification's PersonShape example line by line, we need four pieces of vocabulary that the specification uses dozens of times in every section. These four terms are the load-bearing structure of the entire standard, and they are the ones learners most often blur together. A correct response describes shapes graph accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00145", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_962a61fac632f3e2", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with shapes graph clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Before we read the SHACL specification's PersonShape example line by line, we need four pieces of vocabulary that the specification uses dozens of times in every section. These four terms are the load-bearing structure of the entire standard, and they are the ones learners most often blur together. A rough response alludes to shapes graph loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about shapes graph in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 161, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00145", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00145]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#56204d5fd74aa93f"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#799d33b7bb4efa68"}]}
{"chosen": "Conceptually, the SHACL processor walks every shape in the shapes graph, asks each shape \"which nodes in the data graph are your focus nodes?\", and then for each focus node walks every constraint the shape declares, recording violations. The output is one RDF graph — the validation report — whose root sh:ValidationReport node carries an sh:conforms boolean (true when no constraint was... A correct response describes shapes graph accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00146", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_f91fee726fc4f933", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-18", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with shapes graph clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Conceptually, the SHACL processor walks every shape in the shapes graph, asks each shape \"which nodes in the data graph are your focus nodes?\", and then for each focus node walks every constraint the shape declares, recording violations. The output is one RDF graph — the validation report — whose root sh:ValidationReport node carries an sh:conforms boolean (true when no constraint was... A rough response alludes to shapes graph loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about shapes graph in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 162, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00146", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00146]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#56204d5fd74aa93f"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#799d33b7bb4efa68"}]}
{"chosen": "RDF was designed under the open-world assumption : the absence of a triple in your graph does not mean the fact is false — it simply means your graph does not know about it. This is exactly the right default for building a web of data where no one participant is authoritative. A correct response describes reusability accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00143", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_a19a73fba183c17a", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-18", "co-19", "co-22", "to-04", "to-05"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with reusability clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "RDF was designed under the open-world assumption : the absence of a triple in your graph does not mean the fact is false — it simply means your graph does not know about it. This is exactly the right default for building a web of data where no one participant is authoritative. A rough response alludes to reusability loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of reusability aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 159, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00143", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00143]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#799d33b7bb4efa68"}, {"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#d8e872e61b826838"}]}
{"chosen": "SHACL's cleanest architectural decision is the separation between the shapes graph — the graph that contains the rules — and the data graph — the graph you are validating. Both are ordinary RDF graphs. A correct response describes reusability accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00144", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_79cb45f75a655e8d", "lo_refs": ["co-16", "co-19", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with reusability clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "SHACL's cleanest architectural decision is the separation between the shapes graph — the graph that contains the rules — and the data graph — the graph you are validating. Both are ordinary RDF graphs. A rough response alludes to reusability loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about reusability in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 160, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00144", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00144]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#799d33b7bb4efa68"}, {"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#d8e872e61b826838"}]}
