{"chosen": "The combinator expressions are what give node expressions their compositional power. A path expression takes a node expression and a property path and returns the set of values reachable by walking the path from each input node — equivalent to a SPARQL property path traversal but expressed declaratively. A correct response describes functions node expressions readable accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00184", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_a5a5afa12446f0cb", "lo_refs": ["co-21", "co-18", "co-19", "co-22", "to-05", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with functions node expressions readable clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "The combinator expressions are what give node expressions their compositional power. A path expression takes a node expression and a property path and returns the set of values reachable by walking the path from each input node — equivalent to a SPARQL property path traversal but expressed declaratively. A rough response alludes to functions node expressions readable loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of functions node expressions readable aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 200, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00184", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00184]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.92, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_advanced_features_accessible#312d513458f95e8c"}, {"confidence": 0.9, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_advanced_features_accessible#6d7011e3b1420dcf"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_advanced_features_accessible#13aa21cb2297e73f"}]}
{"chosen": "Common Pitfall: treating sh:not as \"value not in list\" When learners first reach for negation in SHACL, they reach for sh:not because the name is direct. That instinct is correct in many cases — sh:not is the right tool for \"value does not conform to a shape\". A correct response describes heuristic accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00191", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_b15f71f1e7aca5aa", "lo_refs": ["co-19", "co-18", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_c6812491c280bc55", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about heuristic. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with heuristic, \"sh:not means logical negation, and sh:in tests membership in a list, so to forbid a property's value from being one of :Suspended, :Closed, or :Frozen I'll write sh:not [ sh:path :status ; sh:in (:Suspended :Closed :Frozen) ] and it should produce a clean negation.\" This treats sh:not as if it were a value-level negation operator that re-uses sh:in as its inner predicate.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 207, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00191", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00191]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.92, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#6fa327ca3fc0519c"}]}
{"bloom_level": "understand", "chosen": "Only SHACL-SPARQL processors execute them. A Core-only processor parses the shape but produces no validation results for it — silent under-validation.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00173", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_1b3f3d5286250c31", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00173_028", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-20", "to-04", "co-19", "co-22", "to-05"], "lo_refs": ["co-20", "to-04", "co-19", "co-22", "to-05"], "misconception_id": "mc_337070bf2fd883d8", "prompt": "Explain pre deploy checklist clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "Every SHACL processor executes sh:sparql constraints.", "seed": 28, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00173", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00173]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.95, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_spec_accessible#02ea99969917b186"}, {"confidence": 0.85, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "contributing", "sourceId": "dart:shacl_advanced_features_accessible#617dabe19b2eff95"}]}
