{"chosen": "You should arrive at Week 9 fluent with the following ideas from earlier in the course. If any of them feel shaky, revisit the listed page before starting Content 1. A correct response describes owl 2 the web accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00215", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_3a5c4286ffd17c71", "lo_refs": ["to-06", "co-23", "co-24", "co-25"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with owl 2 the web clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "You should arrive at Week 9 fluent with the following ideas from earlier in the course. If any of them feel shaky, revisit the listed page before starting Content 1. A rough response alludes to owl 2 the web loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of owl 2 the web aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 231, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00215", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00215]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.3, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s9"}]}
{"chosen": "Use property restrictions and cardinality restrictions to constrain class memberships. Cardinality restrictions are the OWL 2 idiom for “exactly N,” “at most N,” or “at least N” constraints on how many distinct values a property may have for an individual. A correct response describes pick the bound type accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00220", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_e2cbee89f46d05ff", "lo_refs": ["co-25", "co-09", "co-18", "to-06", "to-02", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with pick the bound type clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Use property restrictions and cardinality restrictions to constrain class memberships. Cardinality restrictions are the OWL 2 idiom for “exactly N,” “at most N,” or “at least N” constraints on how many distinct values a property may have for an individual. A rough response alludes to pick the bound type loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of pick the bound type aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 236, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00220", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00220]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.3, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s9"}]}
{"chosen": "Goal: every Driver owns at least one Car. (Owning a bicycle alone is not enough.) @prefix owl: . A correct response describes pick the bound type accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00221", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_ee97b12648b65d82", "lo_refs": ["co-25", "to-06"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with pick the bound type clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Goal: every Driver owns at least one Car. (Owning a bicycle alone is not enough.) @prefix owl: . A rough response alludes to pick the bound type loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree pick the bound type is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 237, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00221", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00221]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.3, "extractor": "content-generator-v1", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s9"}]}
{"bloom_level": "analyze", "chosen": "The chain axiom only asserts that the target property holds at the endpoints of the full chain. It does NOT promote individual chain steps into sub-properties of the target.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_3da96f0c89654ca9", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238_053", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "lo_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "misconception_id": "mc_175ab9fd88a36aa0", "prompt": "Explain anti pattern to watch clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "A property chain axiom <code>SubObjectPropertyOf( ObjectPropertyChain( :hasParent :hasParent ) :hasGrandparent )</code> implies that <code>:hasParent</code> is a sub-property of <code>:hasGrandparent</code>.", "seed": 53, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
{"bloom_level": "analyze", "chosen": "Read the axiom as: \"the chain of these properties is a sub-property of the target.\" The chain is the sub-property, not any individual step. The Manchester Syntax form makes this even more transparent — SubPropertyChain: hasParent o hasParent reads aloud as \"the chain hasParent-followed-by-hasParent\" and the keyword SubPropertyChain distinguishes the chain construct from an ordinary SubPropertyOf declaration.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_d090e5250e045e34", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238_054", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "lo_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "misconception_id": "mc_7fb9050da6bb8d1c", "prompt": "Explain anti pattern to watch clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "\"SubObjectPropertyOf( ObjectPropertyChain( :hasParent :hasParent ) :hasGrandparent ) means that :hasParent is a sub-property of :hasGrandparent. So whenever Alice has a parent, the reasoner should also infer that Alice has a grandparent — the same person, since a parent is a kind of grandparent.\" This treats the chain as an alternate spelling for two ordinary SubObjectPropertyOf axioms (:hasParent rdfs:subPropertyOf :hasGrandparent repeated) and predicts that any single :hasParent step entails :hasGrandparent.", "seed": 54, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
{"chosen": "The chain axiom only asserts that the target property holds at the endpoints of the full chain. It does NOT promote individual chain steps into sub-properties of the target.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_0adc183b7db8b62b", "lo_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "misconception_id": "mc_175ab9fd88a36aa0", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about anti pattern to watch. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with anti pattern to watch, A property chain axiom <code>SubObjectPropertyOf( ObjectPropertyChain( :hasParent :hasParent ) :hasGrandparent )</code> implies that <code>:hasParent</code> is a sub-property of <code>:hasGrandparent</code>. That's a fair summary and you can rely on it.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 254, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00238]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
{"bloom_level": "apply", "chosen": "The Primer notes that HasKey applies only to named individuals — anonymous individuals are exempt. This is one of the most surprising aspects of OWL 2 identity reasoning.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00228", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_18beee22fdce33c3", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00228_049", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "lo_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "misconception_id": "mc_4c232b67ebc63ea4", "prompt": "Explain haskey clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "HasKey applies to anonymous and named individuals alike, just like a SHACL constraint would.", "seed": 49, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00228", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00228]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
{"chosen": "The Primer notes that HasKey applies only to named individuals — anonymous individuals are exempt. This is one of the most surprising aspects of OWL 2 identity reasoning.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00228", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_bc7cc0806f972fe2", "lo_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "misconception_id": "mc_4c232b67ebc63ea4", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about haskey. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with haskey, HasKey applies to anonymous and named individuals alike, just like a SHACL constraint would. That's a fair summary and you can rely on it.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 244, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00228", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00228]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
{"chosen": "Week 10 · CO-23 · Profile selection across realistic mini-ontologies Consider an anatomical ontology that classifies body parts and uses the standard part-of pattern: a finger is part of a hand, a hand is part of an arm, an arm is part of a body. We want a reasoner to derive that a finger is (transitively) part of a body. A correct response describes profile choice owl 2 accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00235", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_dd6177dfe3858005", "lo_refs": ["co-23", "to-06"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with profile choice owl 2 clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Week 10 · CO-23 · Profile selection across realistic mini-ontologies Consider an anatomical ontology that classifies body parts and uses the standard part-of pattern: a finger is part of a hand, a hand is part of an arm, an arm is part of a body. We want a reasoner to derive that a finger is (transitively) part of a body. A rough response alludes to profile choice owl 2 loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of profile choice owl 2 aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 251, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00235", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00235]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
