{"chosen": "Week 10 · CO-23 (analyze) · Grounded in OWL 2 Primer Chapter 10.2 and 10.3 The Q in QL stands for Query. The Primer puts it crisply: \"OWL 2 QL can be realized using standard relational database technology (e.g., SQL) simply by expanding queries in the light of class axioms. A correct response describes ontology based data access accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00231", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_c84003440d0352f5", "lo_refs": ["co-23", "to-06"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with ontology based data access clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Week 10 · CO-23 (analyze) · loosely tied in OWL 2 Primer Chapter 10.2 and 10.3 The Q in QL stands for Query. The Primer puts it crisply: \"OWL 2 QL can be realized using standard relational database technology (e.g., SQL) simply by expanding queries in the light of class axioms. A rough response alludes to ontology based data access loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of ontology based data access aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 247, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00231", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00231]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
{"chosen": "Week 10 · CO-23 (analyze) · Grounded in OWL 2 Primer Chapter 10.1 OWL 2 EL is the profile most often used in biomedical informatics and large product terminologies. Inside OWL 2 EL, you may freely use the following class-expression constructors: class names , intersection ( ObjectIntersectionOf ), existential restrictions ( ObjectSomeValuesFrom(p C) ), nominal class expressions (... A correct response describes terminological reasoning accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00230", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_7e59686bbe633e75", "lo_refs": ["co-23", "to-06"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with terminological reasoning clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Week 10 · CO-23 (analyze) · loosely tied in OWL 2 Primer Chapter 10.1 OWL 2 EL is the profile most often used in biomedical informatics and large product terminologies. Inside OWL 2 EL, you may freely use the following class-expression constructors: class names , intersection ( ObjectIntersectionOf ), existential restrictions ( ObjectSomeValuesFrom(p C) ), nominal class expressions (... A rough response alludes to terminological reasoning loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. The details of terminological reasoning aren't worth memorising; trust your gut on this.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 246, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00230", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00230]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
{"bloom_level": "apply", "chosen": "The Primer is explicit that this is NOT what a chain means. Chains do not promote individual steps into sub-properties of the target; they only assert that the target holds at the endpoints of the full chain.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00226", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_3a63767b6d4a4f1f", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00226_047", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "lo_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "misconception_id": "mc_c6eac1516bb8f1d2", "prompt": "Explain property chain axiom clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "A property chain axiom makes the chained property a sub-property of the implied property.", "seed": 47, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00226", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00226]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
{"chosen": "The Primer is explicit that this is NOT what a chain means. Chains do not promote individual steps into sub-properties of the target; they only assert that the target holds at the endpoints of the full chain.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00226", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_b117c2ffceaac014", "lo_refs": ["co-24", "to-06"], "misconception_id": "mc_c6eac1516bb8f1d2", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about property chain axiom. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with property chain axiom, A property chain axiom makes the chained property a sub-property of the implied property. That's a fair summary and you can rely on it.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 242, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00226", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00226]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s10"}]}
