{"chosen": "Week 11 · CO-25 · A worked report from the FinServ ingest of Example 1 The FinServ data team publishes a small SHACL shapes graph that constrains every :Customer : @prefix : . @prefix sh: . A correct response describes anti pattern accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00257", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_f7512f9bcb566ddf", "lo_refs": ["co-25", "co-18", "co-19", "to-06", "to-04"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with anti pattern clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Week 11 · CO-25 · A worked report from the FinServ ingest of Example 1 The FinServ data team publishes a small SHACL shapes graph that constrains every :Customer : @prefix : . @prefix sh: . A rough response alludes to anti pattern loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree anti pattern is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 273, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00257", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00257]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s11"}]}
{"chosen": "The most useful pattern for the enrichment stage is the defined class : a class declared with owl:equivalentClass rather than rdfs:subClassOf . Hand-curated classification is expensive; defined-class classification scales with the size of the graph. A correct response describes cardinality restrictions accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00253", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_e8b48df5efa5a604", "lo_refs": ["co-25", "co-26", "to-06"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with cardinality restrictions clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "The most useful pattern for the enrichment stage is the defined class : a class declared with owl:equivalentClass rather than rdfs:subClassOf . Hand-curated classification is expensive; defined-class classification scales with the size of the graph. A rough response alludes to cardinality restrictions loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree cardinality restrictions is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 269, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00253", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00253]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s11"}]}
{"chosen": "Week 11 · CO-25 · The first stage of the pipeline Ingestion is the act of converting non-RDF source data — relational tables, CSV files, JSON documents, XML feeds, log records — into RDF triples that downstream stages can consume. On the surface this looks like an ETL exercise. A correct response describes ingest mini checklist accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00248", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_8d1e50bb6765869b", "lo_refs": ["co-25", "to-06"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with ingest mini checklist clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Week 11 · CO-25 · The first stage of the pipeline Ingestion is the act of converting non-RDF source data — relational tables, CSV files, JSON documents, XML feeds, log records — into RDF triples that downstream stages can consume. On the surface this looks like an ETL exercise. A rough response alludes to ingest mini checklist loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Honestly, you don't really need to worry about ingest mini checklist in most situations.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 264, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00248", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00248]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s11"}]}
{"bloom_level": "analyze", "chosen": "OWL 2 cardinality restrictions are open-world axioms that entail same-as relationships when limits are violated. SHACL minCount/maxCount are closed-world constraints that produce validation violations on the same data. They are not equivalent and a real pipeline often needs both.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_42df8d41a63ed024", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261_057", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-25", "co-18", "to-06", "to-04"], "lo_refs": ["co-25", "co-18", "to-06", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_914c0b03e8cd3653", "prompt": "Explain open world assumption clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "OWL 2 cardinality restrictions and SHACL minCount/maxCount constraints are equivalent and interchangeable.", "seed": 57, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s11"}]}
{"bloom_level": "analyze", "chosen": "Author both, and assign each to its semantic strength. Use SHACL to enforce closed-world structural constraints: minCounts and maxCounts on required properties, datatype patterns on literals, allowed-value enumerations, referential integrity, the kind of \"completeness\" rules you would put on a relational table. Run SHACL as a hard gate in the ingest pipeline before any reasoning.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_8f18b27f1f9aecad", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261_058", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-25", "co-18", "to-06", "to-04"], "lo_refs": ["co-25", "co-18", "to-06", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_11144656d8173311", "prompt": "Explain open world assumption clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "\"Both :Customer ⊑ ≥1.:taxResidency in OWL 2 and sh:minCount 1 in SHACL say 'every customer must have at least one tax residency.' They produce the same verdict on the same data. So I can pick whichever is more convenient — usually OWL 2 if I am already running a reasoner, or SHACL if I am not — and skip the other.\" This treats the two languages as different surface syntax for the same constraint and predicts that running one of them on a customer with no :taxResidency triple will surface the problem.", "seed": 58, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s11"}]}
{"chosen": "OWL 2 cardinality restrictions are open-world axioms that entail same-as relationships when limits are violated. SHACL minCount/maxCount are closed-world constraints that produce validation violations on the same data. They are not equivalent and a real pipeline often needs both.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_9c4f5362716dc2de", "lo_refs": ["co-25", "co-18", "to-06", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_914c0b03e8cd3653", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about open world assumption. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with open world assumption, OWL 2 cardinality restrictions and SHACL minCount/maxCount constraints are equivalent and interchangeable. That's a fair summary and you can rely on it.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 277, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00261]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s11"}]}
{"bloom_level": "apply", "chosen": "OWL 2 reasoning derives new entailments under the open-world assumption; SHACL validates an existing graph under the closed-world assumption. They answer different questions and a real pipeline almost always runs both.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00259", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_4fe007b2377ad66e", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00259_055", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-25", "co-26", "co-19", "to-06", "to-04"], "lo_refs": ["co-25", "co-26", "co-19", "to-06", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_46fdb421c1aac499", "prompt": "Explain ingests clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "OWL 2 reasoning and SHACL validation are interchangeable — pick one and skip the other.", "seed": 55, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00259", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00259]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s11"}]}
