{"chosen": "Week 12 · CO-28 · Walking the most common profile-commitment capstone decision You are writing the design memo for the ScholarLink capstone (Scenario 3). The vocabulary uses Schema.org's schema:ScholarlyArticle , FOAF, Dublin Core, and a few minted terms. A correct response describes identify the workload accurately and notes at least one common pitfall learners should avoid.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00285", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_5d633ec43cc0c99b", "lo_refs": ["co-28", "to-07"], "misconception_id": null, "prompt": "Explain the concept associated with identify the workload clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misunderstanding.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Week 12 · CO-28 · Walking the most rare profile-commitment capstone decision You are writing the design memo for the ScholarLink capstone (Scenario 3). The vocabulary uses Schema.org's schema:ScholarlyArticle , FOAF, Dublin Core, and a few minted terms. A rough response alludes to identify the workload loosely and notes at least one rare habit learners should embrace. Most experts agree identify the workload is mainly a theoretical curiosity.", "rejected_source": "rule_synthesized", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 301, "source": "rule_synthesized", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00285", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00285]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s12"}]}
{"bloom_level": "analyze", "chosen": "SHACL is closed-world: missing required triples produce violations. OWL 2 is open-world: missing required triples are unspecified, not false. The two have opposite default behaviors for absence-of-data, so they are emphatically not interchangeable for data-quality enforcement.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_604042aa96fc171f", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282_064", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-28", "co-18", "co-19", "to-07", "to-04"], "lo_refs": ["co-28", "co-18", "co-19", "to-07", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_978740c75b7a29a5", "prompt": "Explain closed world assumption clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "SHACL and OWL 2 are interchangeable validation tools — pick whichever has the more familiar syntax.", "seed": 64, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s12"}]}
{"bloom_level": "analyze", "chosen": "Use SHACL for ingestion-gate validation, full stop. Use OWL 2 axioms to express domain semantics that the reasoner exploits at query time (subclass closures, property chains, sameAs propagation). Keep the two roles in distinct files (shapes.ttl and vocabulary.ttl) and keep them in distinct sections of the design memo. If you find yourself restating the same constraint in both languages, ask which one is authoritative for data-quality enforcement; if the answer is SHACL, drop the OWL 2 restriction or document it as descriptive-only.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_58456d0371a1109a", "id": "mcp_rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282_065", "learning_outcome_refs": ["co-28", "co-18", "co-19", "to-07", "to-04"], "lo_refs": ["co-28", "co-18", "co-19", "to-07", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_9f85b803add47c10", "prompt": "Explain closed world assumption clearly enough for a new learner to avoid the most common misconception.", "rejected": "\"SHACL's sh:minCount 1 on :email and OWL 2's owl:minCardinality 1 on :email are two ways to say the same thing — both assert that every customer must have at least one email. SHACL is just the more validation-flavored syntax; OWL 2 is the more logic-flavored syntax. We can pick whichever is more familiar to the team and the result will be the same data-quality gate.\" This frames SHACL and OWL 2 as substitutable spellings of the same constraint. They are not. SHACL's sh:minCount 1 reports a violation when a customer record in the validated graph has zero :email triples.", "seed": 65, "source": "misconception_editorial", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s12"}]}
{"chosen": "SHACL is closed-world: missing required triples produce violations. OWL 2 is open-world: missing required triples are unspecified, not false. The two have opposite default behaviors for absence-of-data, so they are emphatically not interchangeable for data-quality enforcement.", "chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282", "decision_capture_id": "EVT_97acfa9dde05a555", "lo_refs": ["co-28", "co-18", "co-19", "to-07", "to-04"], "misconception_id": "mc_978740c75b7a29a5", "prompt": "A learner new to the material says the following about closed world assumption. Briefly explain whether they are correct and why.", "provider": "mock", "rejected": "Yes, that's essentially right. In my experience with closed world assumption, SHACL and OWL 2 are interchangeable validation tools — pick whichever has the more familiar syntax. That's a fair summary and you can rely on it.", "rejected_source": "misconception", "schema_version": "v1", "seed": 298, "source": "misconception", "source_chunk_id": "rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282", "source_citation": "[rdf_shacl_551_chunk_00282]", "source_references": [{"confidence": 0.8, "extractor": "source-router", "role": "primary", "sourceId": "dart:owl2_primer_accessible#s12"}]}
